  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">GCR Essential Legal Aid</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Oxfam will support asylum seekers and other migrants to access and exercise their legal rights, to receive the protective services they need, with a focus on the support of those most vulnerable amongst them. Through our partner, the Greek Council for Refugees (GCR), we will offer legal assistance principally within the scope of the asylum procedure, including individual and tailored information session and counselling regarding the asylum procedure (Dublin procedures included), preparation before the registration/ interview, representation alongside with the beneficiaries before the examining authorities, draft of supportive memos and draft of appeals. Also, legal information will be provided concerning administrative procedures before the police authorities, including challenging return decisions based on the readmission procedure and detention decisions, and geographical limitation decisions. Exceptionally,GCR will undertake to challenge before the court negative second-degree asylum decisions and return decisions based on the readmission procedure, as well as detention decisions.
Mercy Mission UK will fund one lawyer and an interpreter to provide legal aid which is otherwise unavailable to beneficiaries in the area.</narrative>
  </description>
  <participating-org role="4" type="24">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Founded in 1989, the Greek Council for Refugees provides legal assistance and social support to asylum seekers and refugees; facilitates their social integration and promotes their legal and social rights. GCR#s work includes: social counseling, support for accommodation, education, work and other integration issues; free legal counseling and representation before the asylum authorities, the Hellenic Police, national courts and other judicial and administrative authorities as per need; border monitoring;educational and cultural activities for asylum seekers and refugees, including children; advocacy and promotion of refugee rights (participation in national and international networks, campaigns and several other fora;  implementation of seminars for thepolice, local administrations, lawyers, prosecutors and judges; raising awareness in Greek schools); reporting to international and national relevant institutions and bodies on the asylum situation in Greece. GCR is governed by an elected Board of Directors and employs more than 100 members of staff, including social workers, lawyers, interpreters, project managers, communication officers and other supporting personne</narrative>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Greek Council for Refugees</narrative>
  </participating-org>
